,Recommended,216890,7875668,"Posted: 1 December, 2013",all,Patches,"It's one of my ""go to"" games when I get bored. It's an interesting game, but you have to be prepared for failure as the odds are amost always in favor of failing... But that's how Game's Workshop games are. To properly enjoy the game you have to accept that you might lose or that a play won't go favorably. It's definitely a game about minimizing your chances at failing, it's part of the strategy and you can use it against your opponents.Personally, I like playing the Ogre team. They don't seem like a serious team, but fielding 6 big guys really puts the hurt on the enemy team. Every injury is like an extra point in my book."
76561198028095122,Recommended,216890,8029694,"Posted: 13 December, 2013",all,Case_Number,"This is a hard game to recommend to anyone.  Every time I start describing the experience of carefully selecting a team, training them, picking a sponsor and selecting your per-game bribes people get excited.  Then people hear that in every match there's a chance that your entire team will be injured or killed after gaining valuable experience points.  People's eyes tend to glaze over at this point.It's the violence and death that make the multiplayer and campaign so good.  You know that every match will be brutal and chance as much as skill will turn the tide of victory.  Seeing the crowd turn on your opponent to tear them to shreds on a bad play or watching your own blocker critically fail a roll and bounce off the other teams ball carrier like the dude is made of force fields are just flipsides of the same coin.You can be good at this game or bad.  Awesome or terrible.  In the end this game is like all true Games Workshop titles.  Skill is irrelevant.  The fun is in the stories you get to tell later about the crazy stuff that happened on the dice rolls and how they played out.  Play it with friends or enemies or the exceptionally active Blood Bowl community on Steam if you like, but understand that winning and losing aren't super important.  It's all about how the game plays you."
