,Recommended,216890,9735774,"Posted: 5 April, 2014",all,Foghorn Dickhorn,"Very high learning curve, fairly faithful adaptation of the board game.It is unfortunately not ""Full featured"" as some of the star players are missing and some skills don't work quite right, but it's pretty close, and a good substitute for spending a couple hundred dollars on minatures and spending a weekend with a bunch of sweaty geeks.If you get frustrated easily, this game will not be for you.  The amount of times you seem to fail die rolls while the computer doesn't will aggravate you to no end until you understand all of the rules of the game, at which point the AI will be a pathetic competitor, providing no challenge at all.  Given all that, you can still get many hundreds of hours out of it, fine tuning your strategy in single player, playing many different races in many different manners.The online league interface is unfortunately a little haphazard.  League management controls are somewhat limited and not as fleshed out as I'd like them to be, but it's entirely serviceable.  Random online matchmaking does exist, but you'll notice that the matching system isn't based upon skill as much as it is based upon cheesing the system, by using teams at their specific overpowered points in the rankings.  Really where the game shines is in a league setting with 16 or more like minded individuals in a structured season/playoff format.  I ran an online league for several seasons, and most of the guys would agree it was an incredible amount of fun, even when their team was getting destroyed.It is a pretty niche game, but if you fit that niche, you will enjoy it to no end.  Or complain about the RNG and never play it again.  One or the other."
