76561197981955527,Recommended,216890,19020229,"Posted: 11 November, 2015",all,spoonlamp,"This is a tricksy game for me to recommend outright, but only because of the price. I picked it up in the Steam sale for £4.99 (iirc) and for that money I would say ""don't miss it!"". Turn based, simple concept, yet very complicated in the hands of skilled players, it's a rare game which has a long term draw. A cursory understanding of dice probability will be of huge help for those (like me) who might quit in a rage with the words ""cheating computer!"" when it seems like the AI teams are always passing their dice checks and I always fail mine! (it only seems that way!)Long term players unanimously denounce the single player AI as useless although coming almost from fresh I'll say it's enough to give you the basic concepts and will punish mistakes. There are plenty of online leagues for you to cut your teeth on  and there is a healthy fan-base of regular players - the ideal place to learn not to get too attached to your players ;)If you are looking at this and wondering whether to get it or Blood Bowl 2, I'll have to say I'm a little torn myself. There are plenty of threads for comparisons, but I think the key point is that those who have played these old editions are happy with where the balances are and the content (EVERY team). The new game (BB2) has changed a lot of things and in some areas this has actually broken some of the game blance, but someone completely new to Blood Bowl might not actually be affected by this. And the devs are finally listening to customer feedback and implementing some good positive changes.For me it comes down to price though.  The game is like chess, in that while it's a simple concept, in the hands of good players it develops layers of intelligent enjoyment which the new version simply glosses up. if this turns up in the sale again grab it - and remember - those dice rolls really are random!  ;)"
